<P>Ref.: 1123=20
<P>
<P>
<H1>ISO/IEC DIS 29500 receives necessary votes for approval as an =
International=20
Standard </H1>
<P></P>
<P>
<H3>2008-04-02 </H3>
<P>ISO/IEC DIS 29500, <EM>Information technology =E2=80=93 Office Open =
XML file=20
formats</EM>, has received the necessary number of votes for approval as =
an=20
ISO/IEC International Standard. </P>
<P>Approval required at least 2/3 (i.e. 66.66 %) of the votes cast by =
national=20
bodies participating in the joint technical committee ISO/IEC JTC 1,=20
<EM>Information technology</EM>, to be positive; and no more than 1/4 =
(i.e. 25=20
%) of the total number of ISO/IEC national body votes cast to be =
negative. These=20
criteria have now been met with 75 % of the JTC 1 participating member =
votes=20
cast positive and 14 % of the total of national member body votes cast=20
negative.</P>
<P>The 30-day period during which ISO/IEC national bodies had the =
opportunity to=20
reconsider their votes on the draft ISO/IEC DIS 29500 closed at midnight =
on=20
Saturday, 29 March 2008, with the result that the criteria for approval =
of the=20
document as an ISO/IEC International Standard have now been met.</P>
<P>ISO/IEC DIS 29500 was originally disapproved in the "fast-track =
vote"which=20
ended in September 2007, when 3 500 comments were received. However, =
under the=20
rules of ISO/IEC JTC 1, the DIS vote was followed by a ballot resolution =
meeting=20
(BRM) at which the comments were addressed. After the meeting, the =
ISO/IEC=20
national bodies had 30 days to modify their votes if they wished.</P>
<P>The BRM was held in Geneva during the week 25-29 February 2008. By=20
eliminating redundancies, the comments had been reduced to just over 1 =
000=20
individual issues to be considered. Issues considered as priorities by =
national=20
members (such as accessibility, date formats, conformance issues) were=20
discussed, and the other comments were addressed through a voting =
process on the=20
remaining items, a system agreed by the BRM participants.</P>
<P>The issues addressed and revised have resulted in sufficient national =
bodies=20
withdrawing their earlier disapproval votes, or transforming them into =
positive=20
votes, so that the criteria for approval of the document as an =
International=20
Standard have now been met. Subject to there being no formal appeals =
from=20
ISO/IEC national bodies in the next two months, the International =
Standard will=20
accordingly proceed to publication. </P>
<P>ISO/IEC 29500 is a standard for word-processing documents, =
presentations and=20
spreadsheets that is intended to be implemented by multiple applications =
on=20
multiple platforms. According to the submitters of the document, one of =
its=20
objectives is to ensure the long-term preservation of documents created =
over the=20
last two decades using programmes that are becoming incompatible with =
continuing=20
advances in the field of information technology.</P>
<P>ISO/IEC DIS 29500 was originally developed as the Office Open XML=20
Specification by Microsoft Corporation which submitted it to Ecma =
International,=20
an information technology industry association, for transposing into an =
ECMA=20
standard. Following a process in which other IT industry players =
participated,=20
Ecma International subsequently published the document as ECMA standard =
376.</P>
<P>Ecma International then submitted the standard in December 2006 to =
ISO/IEC=20
JTC 1, with whom it has category A liaison status, for adoption as an=20
International Standard under the JTC 1 "fast track" procedure. This =
allows a=20
standard developed within the IT industry to be presented to JTC 1 as a =
draft=20
international standard (DIS) that can be adopted after a process of =
review and=20
balloting. This process has now been concluded with the end of the =
30-day period=20
following the ballot resolution meeting.</P>
<P>The process was open to the IEC and ISO national member bodies from =
104=20
countries, including 41 that are participating members of the joint =
ISO/IEC JTC=20
1.</P>
<P>
